article.description: Becky Hammon had 10 of her 12 points in the second half, helping the New York Liberty end a five-game losing streak against the defending WNBA champion Detroit Shock with a 64-52 victory Wednesday night.
article.headline: Liberty finally stops slump vs. Shock
article.linkText: Liberty starters in double digits as NY shocks Detroit
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty showed the Detroit Shock
just how much they've improved.

Becky Hammon had 10 of her 12 points in the second half, and all
five starters scored in double figures as the Liberty ended a
five-game losing streak against the defending WNBA champions with a
64-52 victory Wednesday night.

"We really got everyone involved," Hammon said. "That is how
we are going to beat teams, by playing together."

Crystal Robinson and Tari Phillips had 13 points apiece, Vickie
Johnson added 11, and Elena Baranova missed getting her third
straight double-double, finishing with 11 points, nine rebounds and
five assists.

"This was a great win for us," New York coach Richie Adubato
said. "Our defense was the best we have played in a long time. We
had balanced scoring."

The Liberty shot 26-for-58 from the field (44.8 percent),
including 6-for-13 (46 percent) on 3-pointers.

Cheryl Ford, last season's rookie of the year, had 12 points and
14 rebounds for the Shock before fouling out with 3:20 remaining.

New York beat Detroit for the first time since June 9, 2002, and
limited the Shock to just 18 points in the second half on 6-for-27
shooting (22.2 percent). They were 20-for-60 (33 percent) overall
and committed 24 turnovers, including nine by Swin Cash.

"We didn't play as hard as we needed to," Detroit coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "We didn't play with enough concentration. I think
that was the biggest key for us tonight. We knew they were going to
be a better team than last year. They added some pieces, they're a
little bit bigger. They can score in all positions now."

Trailing 34-33 at halftime, the Liberty went on a 16-6 run to
take a nine-point lead six minutes into the second half. Hammon had
eight points during that stretch.

"She's a great shooter and they're pushing the ball a lot more
than they did last year," Shock center Ruth Riley said.

New York's lead was at least seven the rest of the way, and
reached 15, at 64-49, on Johnson's 16-foot jumper with 1:32
remaining.

"They did not play their best game," Adubato said. "They
threw the ball away a lot, which is uncharacteristic of them. We
can't take credit for that. What we can take credit for is we
challenged every shot and made them take tough shots."

Detroit scored the game's first five points for its biggest lead
of the game, before the Liberty scored seven straight points to
take their first lead.

The score was tied eight times in the first half, and New York
took it's biggest lead of the period at 29-22 on Robinson's layup
with just over five minutes left.

Ford scored four points in the final minute with a layup and an
11-foot jumper to give the Shock a three-point lead.

Johnson hit a 19-footer to cut New York's deficit to one heading
into the half.
